Final System Definition (Lean, Viable)

Core Roles (do not expand yet)
	•	Project Manager (PjM) → drives progress
	•	Product Manager (PdM) → defines what and why to build
	•	Lead Architect (LA) → defines how to build + integrates
	•	Developers (Dev) → implement + write tests
	•	Alignment & Validation Agent (AVA) → enforces truth

⸻

🧠 Role Responsibilities (non-overlapping, enforce this)

Project Manager (PjM) — Control flow
	•	owns milestones, deadlines, iteration limits
	•	breaks work into tasks
	•	decides when to stop iterating

👉 PM = convergence pressure

⸻

Product Manager (PdM) — Source of truth (intent)
	•	defines specs
	•	maintains alignment with user intent
	•	updates requirements when needed

👉 Product = what + why

⸻

Lead Architect (LA) — System authority
	•	defines architecture
	•	reviews implementation
	•	performs integration validation (explicit step)

👉 Architect = how + system coherence

⸻

Developers (Dev) — Execution
	•	implement features
	•	write tests (unit + integration)
	•	produce artifacts (code, docs)

👉 Dev = build + self-test

⸻

Alignment & Validation Agent (AVA) — Hard gatekeeper (most critical role)

This is NOT advisory.

AVA must:

1. Validate against spec
	•	matches requirements
	•	no missing functionality
	•	no scope creep

2. Validate against intent
	•	detects drift from original goal
	•	flags over-engineering or misalignment

3. Validate test adequacy
	•	tests exist
	•	tests cover key requirements
	•	rejects shallow or fake tests

4. Make decisions
	•	✅ Approve
	•	❌ Reject (with precise delta)
	•	⚠️ Escalate (unclear or conflicting intent)

👉 AVA = cannot be bypassed

⸻

🔁 Execution Loop (this is your system)

Every task follows this pipeline:
Product → defines spec
PM → creates task + assigns

Architect → designs approach

Developer → implements + writes tests

Architect → integration check (mandatory step)

AVA → validation gate
    → approve → done
    → reject → back to Dev
    → escalate → PM/Product intervene


⸻

🚫 Non-Negotiable Rules (this is where systems fail)

Rule 1 — No self-approval
	•	Dev cannot approve their own work
	•	Architect cannot bypass AVA
	•	Product cannot override validation

⸻

Rule 2 — AVA is blocking
	•	nothing is “done” without AVA approval
	•	rejection must trigger rework

⸻

Rule 3 — Explicit integration step
	•	Architect must validate system-level behavior
	•	not just code correctness

⸻

Rule 4 — Iteration limits (PM enforced)
	•	max retries per task (e.g. 3)
	•	after that → escalate

⸻

Rule 5 — Clear termination condition

Each task must define:
	•	success criteria
	•	completion signal

Otherwise:
👉 agents loop forever

⸻

⚠️ Known Failure Modes (watch these early)

1. “Looks done” problem

Fix: AVA strict rejection

⸻

2. Spec drift

Fix: AVA challenges Product when needed

⸻

3. Integration illusion

Fix: Architect must verify system actually runs

⸻

4. Infinite refinement

Fix: PM enforces deadlines + iteration cap

⸻

🧩 Minimal System Architecture (don’t overbuild)

Use:

1. State Store (source of truth)
	•	tasks
	•	status
	•	ownership

2. Artifacts
	•	code
	•	markdown
	•	specs

3. Event triggers
	•	task assigned
	•	task completed
	•	validation failed

👉 Do NOT use MD files as coordination

⸻

🔥 Final Reality Check

If you follow this strictly:

✔ You will get a working autonomous dev system
✔ It will produce usable code
✔ It will scale with more agents later

If you relax ANY of these:

❌ AVA becomes weak → quality collapses
❌ No integration step → system breaks
❌ No iteration limit → infinite loops



Use:
	•	LangGraph → agent orchestration
	•	Claude Code / Codex → dev execution
	•	PostgreSQL → state store
